{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958020701/0156.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nUNION\nJOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, February 7,1958\nTime For Action\n0\nNE OF THE SHAMES of Ohio is its\nfailure to establish decent minimum\nwage rates for women and minors who\nwork in the laundry, dry cleaning and re\ntail store trades.\nThe minimum of 27 12 cents an hour\nfor the laundry trade has been unchanged\nsince 1934. The minimum of 35 cents an\nhour for the dry cleaning trade has been\nunchanged since 1935. There is no mini\nmum for the retail trade.\nPetitions requesting the appointment\nof wage boards to establish more realistic\nminimums in the laundry and dry clean\ning trades were filed last Friday with Di\nrector Hugh D. Wait of the Ohio Indus\ntrial Relations Board by the Consumers\nLeague of Ohio. They also requested a\nstudy of wage rates in retail trades.\nPolitical pressures from employer\ngroups has kept the minimum rates for\nwomen and minor workers at their pres\nent shameful and disgraceful levels for\nmore than 20 years.\nOhio should have taken the lead long\nbefore this in making certain that women\nand children are being paid decent wages\nand are not being forced to work 50 and\n60 hours a week, but the political pressure\nhas been too great. And so the women and\nminors have lost out.\nWe trust that Mr. Wait will not dilly\ndally in naming the new wage boards.\nThere has been enough of that under past\nstate administrations. What is needed now\nis action!\nNaive Or Deceiving?\nH\nARSH WORDS were voiced by the\nAFL-CIO in describing the Economic\nReport of Pres. Eisenhower, which was\nsent to Congress early in the new session.\nAs the AFL-CIO\u2019s director of research,\nStanley Ruttenberg, put it bluntly in testi\nmony before Congress, the country\u2019s prob\nlems \u201crequire honest reporting and hard\nheaded solutions.\u201d\nBut instead of proposing \u201crealistic\u201d\nsolutions, the Administration has unfolded\n\u201can array of wishful thinking with impli\ncations of dangerous political deception\nInstead of realism, the Economic Report\n\"whistles in the dark\u201d\u2014and the guideposts\nwhich it has chosen to predict the reces\nsion will soon be over are \u201crather blurred\u201d\nand \u201clacking in candor.\u201d\nThese are harsh words, but they badly\nneed saying.\nWashington is full of trained govern\nment officials and expert reporters who\nare saying much the same thing about the\nEconomic Report and the Budget Message\n\u2014but their words are mostly being said\nin private.\nSharp talk, harsh words are not pleas\nant\u2014but if they cut through the fog of\ncomplacency and soft soap that engulfs\nWashington today, they will serve a valu\nable, constructive purpose.\nSUB Praised Again\nEVERAL WEEKS ago we cited a story\n1 in the Wall Street Journal that told\ns\nhow effective the payment of supplemen\ntal unemployment benefits (SUB) had\nbeen in preventing a depression in the\nsteel town of Donora, Pa\nThis week we point to additional evi\ndence from another source that SUB plans\nare good for workers and the economy\u2014a\nroundup story on SUB in the New York\nTimes of January 27.\nThe front-page story by The Times\nnoted labor reporter, A. H Raskin, started\noff with this statement: \u201cUnion manage\nment unemployment benefit funds are\nhelping thousands of jobless workers wea\nther the recession.\"\n\u201cNo accurate estimate is available of\nThrough The Years\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\n15 TEAM AGO\nFebruary 5, 1943\u2014Claiming a substantial\nmembership in the Standard Products Co. at\nPort Clinton, the UAW-CIO filed a brief with\nthe NLRB asking for an election to determine\nwhich shall represent the plant workers, the\nUAW or the company-dominated Booster Club\nSam Hobbs of Alabama, whose labor-bait\ning is a recurring feature of every session of\nthe House, succeeded in having the 78th Con\ngress\u2019 first anti-labor bill reported out of the\nJudiciary Committee Rationing of canned\ngoods will begin sometimes during the month\nof February because of the lend-lease demand.\n19 TEARS AGO\nFebruary 5, 1945: A committee consisting\nof members, women and a civic group will be\nnamed soon to conduct the second annual Lo\ncal 12 Children's Summer Camp drive for\n550,000 to enlarge the camp to accommodate\n2252 children each camping period Re\ncourse to labor's only real weapon, the deci\nsion to strike, brought Chicago s 14,000 school\nteachers their pay checks, which had been held\nup for five weeks because City Council had\nnot taken action on the school budget.\n5 TEARS AGO\nFebruary 5, 1953: CIO President Walter\nReuther pledged improvement of health and\nsocial security provisions in labor-management\ncontracts held by CIO affiliates because of the\nneed of protection from the hazards of illness,\nunemployment and old age Local 12 in\naugurated its series of five minute TV pro\ngrams and will continue to give news of in\nterest to the union members of Toledo.\nt\nthe sum being pumped into the economy\nby all the union-management plans, but it\nprobably will exceed $7,500,000 this\nmonth (January),\u201d the story stated.\nThe Times story said that this sum was\nsmall when compared with the national\ntotal of $250,000,000 that laid-off workers\nwill receive in January through state un\nemployment compensation.\n\u201cHowever,\u201d it added, \u201cthe supplemen\ntary payments have enabled many work\ners to maintain their-purchasing power at\nnearly two-thirds of normal take-home\nstandards, instead of the one-third possible\nthrough sole reliance on their state\nchecks.\u201d (underlining ours)\nReporter Raskin wrote that he had\nfound the general attitude of company\nexecutives \u201ca good deal more hospitable\u201d\nto SUB than when Labor first proposed\nsuch benefit plans three years ago.\nFor example, Raskin reported that an\nindustrial chief of a major steel firm said\nhis firm had \u201cno regrets or apologies for\nthe supplementary benefit program in\nview of the manifest inadequacy of the\nstate insurance systems. We feel that these\npayments have become a valuable econo\nmic bulwark in steel-making communi\nties.\u201d (underlining ours)\nIt is truly tragic that Ohio workers and\nthe state\u2019s economy are being denied the\nbenefits of SUB plans because a handful of\nlobbyists managed to persuade the State\nAdministration that it was politically wise\nto do so!\nDept. Of Split Parties\n\u201cVice President Nixon said tonight the\nDemocratic party is so divided \u2018it is in\ncapable of effectively leading the nation\u2019\nin the space age.\u201d (Associated Press story\nin Cleveland Plain Dealer, Jan. 21)\n\u201cVice President Richard M. Nixon\nsought yesterday to mend the split in the\nRepublican party for the sake of the elec\ntion campaign this year.\u201d (Story in New\nYork Times, Jan. 26)\nVandercook Says:\n(This column is excerpted from the\nnightly broadcasts of John W. Vander\ncook, ABC commentator, sponsored by the\nAFL-CIO. Listen to Vandercook over the\nABC network Monday through Friday at\n10 p.m., EST J\nIN HIS \u201cDear Lyndon\u201d letter to Sen.\nJohnson, refusing to make available to\nCongress the texts of the Gaither and Kil\nlian reports, Pres. Eisenhower fell, back\nupon what Gen. Eisenhower's own army\ncensors used to call a \"previously pre\npared position.\"\nThe chief executive reminded the Sen\nate\u2019s Democratic leader \u201cthat in such a\nmatter as this we must be careful to\nmaintain the proper separation of powers\nbetween the executive and the legislative\nbranches of the government.\u201d\nNo one believes, of course, that the\nUnited States could be efficiently admin\nistered if the President, his cabinet and\nhis bureau chiefs perpetually had Con\ngress looking over their shoulders. In\nmost cases, there\u2019d be little quarrel with\na President\u2019s decision not to tell a con\ngressional committee everything he knew.\nBut, in these instances, a doubt arises.\nThe Gaither report on the state of our de\nfenses and the Killian Committee Report\non the status of scientific progress in the\nU. S., it is believed, do not contain any\naccount of executive deliberations. ac\ntions or decisions.\nThe very fact that the White House is\nso anxious that no one outside of Eisen\nhower\u2019s inner circle should have a glimpse\nof them, indicates that Chairmen Gaither\nand Killian have, rather, put down on\npaper a distressing record of executive in\nactions and indecisions.\nEssentially those reports are accumu\nlations of facts. Pres. Eisenhower himself\nadmits that \u201cthe information given (in\nthem) is essentially the same information\nwhich has been and is available to con\ngressional committees currently studying\nthe same problems.\u201d And facts about the\ncondition of our military and scientific\ndefenses peculiarly are the concern of\nCongress.\nIndeed, the President seems to be say\ning, \u201cI have no objection to your learning\neverything my committee men have\nlearned. But you must dig it out for your\nselves. I won't make it easy for you.\"\nWhen one recalls that no one has sug\ngested that the \u2019genuine military secrets\nin those reports should be babbled to the\nworld, it is hard to avoid the conclusion\nthat the President has taken a strong\nstand on rather weak ground.\nWhat is at issue in both of those re\nports is our national survival. If the facts\nwe\u2019ve already learned are to be believed,\nthe assurance of our survival is going to\ncost a whopping lot of money.\nWe will back big appropriations only\nif we fully understand our situation. The\nGaither and Killian reports could help us\nunderstand. By keeping them secret, the\nPresident is further hampering exactly\nthe kind of scientific, military and imagi\nnative progress, which his administration\nhas already so dangerously hampered in\nthe past.\ni\nDoing His Homework\n.1\n3\n-fa Ad.- bitica\nyS3\nNow It Is Official..\nBy PETE ZVARA\n,411.1111111' iiiii,i>. \u25a0-\u2022.iriri.iiMrtii.Kiiiiiiirii.HuriniivTiiUHiumi M\"MIIMITOMWNTMMNWMNDR*G**44l\"G\nIT IS NOW more or less officially accepted\nthat there are some four million workers\nout of work in our country. Moreover, Labor\nSecretary Mitchell just the other day warned\nthe country that the number of our jobless\nPete Zvara\nmay reach much higher fig\nures, with some people\u2014par\nticularly labor leaders\u2014pre\ndicting that our unemployed\nin the coming months may\nreach as high as six million,\nmaybe more.\nTo add to the seriousness\nof the situation, the word\n\"recession\" no longer seems\nto be a \"dirty\" word for even\nthe mighty New York Times\nadmits in one of its feature\narticles in last Sunday's is\nsue that the \u201crecession\"\u2014not \"depression\"\u2014\nis in fact upon us.\nNow, one may argue the fine points of the\ndifference between a \"recession\" and a \"de\npression\", as does Mr. Henry C Wallich. pro\nfessor of economics at Yale University and the\nauthor of The New York Times article I have\nreference to, the facts are that to our growing\njobless army both these expressions mean\nexactly the same thing; poverty, misery and\nonly too often downright destitution.\nAND UNFORTUNATELY we don't have to\ngo far to prove our point Right here in our\nown Toledo we now have\u2014-and these figures\nare official, direct from the Bureau of Unem\nployment Compensation\u2014 over 17,000 jobless\nworkers\nThe truth is that these figures are highly\ninaccurate and that the actual number of our\njobless is much higher. Actually government\nagencies only keep track of those workers who\nare eligible for unemployment compensation\u2014\nand only during the time they are entitled to\nreceive these benefits. What happens to those\nworkers who work in industries and for small\nbusiness places not covered by unemployment\ncompensation seems to be no concern of these\nsame government agencies.\nFurthermore, tens of thousands of jobless\nworkers have exhausted their benefits and they\nare promptly forgotten, not counted in the\nranks of the jobless. But, of course, this does\nnot mean that they are hack on the job, at\nleast in a large number of cases.\nNOW THERE MAY BE people who feel\nthat we are painting the pictures too dark;\nthat we are, as many accuse us, in reality noth\ning but prophets of \"gloom and doom\nPerhaps, but let us look at the employment\nconditions in some of our largest plants in\nToledo. It is no secret that in a good many of\nour auto supplier plants workers with as much\nas twenty-five years of seniority are laid off.\nAny number of these plants are now operating\non a work force two-thirds below their normal\nlevel.\ni\nAnd, again unfortunately, these conditions\nare not peculiar to Toledo. They are, in fact,\nso widespread that responsible business and'\ngovernment leaders\u2014not to mention trade\nunion officials\u2014are deeply worried about it.\nRight now the steel industry, the most basic of\nour industries, is operating at scarcely half of\nits capacity. Steel production figures tell us\nORGANIZE TOLEDO100%\nOfficial Publication of Organised Labor\nIn Northwestern Ohio\nIR Pl\nSsoceani\nGrand\nAward\nWinner\nEntered at Toledo, Ohio. Post Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug. 24, 1912\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nFor Information Phone CB. 1-9126\nWalter Murphy\nBernard Stern\nWilliam Borden\nDerele Collins\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nEdmond A. PawlickI\nEditor\nAssociate Editor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nJournal Cameramen\nOrville Beemer, Walter Murphy,\nCharles Ballard, Otto Beebe (Local 348),\nErnest Love (Local 1058) Board of Trustees\nDavid Buber\nDirector of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCB. 4-4400 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Union Advertising, N. T.\nthat we are today producing at an annual rate\nof 50.000.000 tons of steel below our operating\nlevel of just one year ago.\nThis means, if this rate of operation keeps\nup for the rest of the year, that we shall have\nlost forever these 50,000,000 tons of steel for\nour country.\nThe loss of this huge amount of steel, of\ncourse, will inevitably reflect itself in all other\nindustries, and that only means multiplying\nthe force of economic recession and the num\nber of our jobless and destitute people.\nBUT NOW THAT everyone seems to admit\nthat our economy is in a recession, everyone\nthat is except Ike and his Republican advisers\nwho still insist that we are suffering from a\nmomentary \u201ceconomic readjustment,\u201d a \u201cbrea\nther following our recent boom,\u201d the problem\nis what to do about it? How can we get back to\nthe high road of economic prosperity that our\npeople and our country must have if we are to\navoid a most serious depression that could re\nsult in perhaps fatal consequences to our free\nenterprise system?\nThere seems to be great confusion in the\nranks of business when its leaders attempt to\nanswer this question. Most of them are united\nagainst every demand by workers and their\nunions for higher wages.\nSome of these people go so far as to call for\na real, hardfisted policy to beat back the un\nions.\n\u201cWe in management must begin now to re\nfuse wage increases even though we know that\nour refusals will produce strikes. We have\nbeen too timid about strikes,\u201d declared in\ndustrialist Leland Hazard, vice president and\ngeneral manager of the Pittsburgh Plate Glass\nCo. in a recent address to some 750 other busi\nness leaders in Philadelphia.\nEven President Eisenhower warned our\nunions about going after unrealistic, or un\nhealthy wage boosts, as he put it\nYet other business leaders seem to counsel\notherwise. Just the other day the editor of\nBusiness Week, perhaps the most influential\npublication in its field, told a Detroit audience\nof business and industrial leaders that the\nFederal Government must step into the situa\ntion now to prevent our current recession from\ndeveloping into a major depression. He sug\ngested that the government take the present\nlull in our economic life to build such neces\nsary things as schools, hospitals, public roads\nand other similar projects.\nAnd he warned the government and his\naudience that it is far better to do \u201ctoo much\u201d\nto stop this economic downturn, then to wind\nup with \"too little and too late.\u201d\nAND WHILE this open debate is going on\nabout our economic life, there are other busi\nness leaders and particularly economists who\npredict that within the next decade our stand\nard of living must rise by at least fifty per\ncent.\nIn' the same Philadelphia banquet where\nMr. Hazard urged his fellow industrialists to\nplunge the nation into a sea of strikes, another\nspeaker, Mr. Arno H. Johnson, vice president\nof the J. Walter Thompson Co. said that \u201ctotal\nsales of goods and services to consumers would\nhave to increase more than 50 per cent within\nthe next decade for the country to keep pace\nwith is increasing productive ability.\"\nEven Vice President Nixon has spoken of\nthe day in the not too distant future when\nworkers would be working four days a week\nand enjoying a standard of living far above\nwhat we have today.\nFine, we say to these people who seem to\nhave so much faith in our future. But, mean\nwhile what do we do about our jobless of\ntoday? How do we help those who are suffer\ning misery and destitution in a land that is the\nrichest, the most blessed in all history?\nThe labor movement says; higher wages,\nmore purchasing power to our people so that\nthey may buy in abundance the necessities of\nlife we produce in our plants.\nIsn't it criminally stupid to permit so many\nof our people, young and old, to go hungry in\na land where our warehouses are bulging\nwith food; in a land where we pay out hun\ndreds of millions of dollars to the farmers not\nto produce more food because we already have\nmore than we can use?\nOr have we?\nWhat a propaganda line for the Communist\nWorld to take in their never ending and bitter\nfight against our system!\nSIGN IN DETROIT STORE window:\nVolkswagen Go Home.\nIts Your Washington\nBy WILLARD SHELTON\nSOMETHING LESS than proper attention has been giv\nen to the news from John A. Hannah, chairman of\nthe Civil Rights Commission authorized in the right-to\nvote law of 1957, that at least four persons have'now re\nfused appointment to the key job of staff director.\nIt is perfectly obvious that anyone who takes this post will\nbe thrusting himself into the jaws of congressional man-eaters.\nHe will be subject to scrutiny first on confirmation by the\nSenate. His views, concepts and basic approaches could be,\nand probably would be. examined in detail in committee hear\nings. Once confirmed, his actions would still be subject to hos\ntile review.\nThe powerful southern bloc in House and Senate was able\nto trim down the proposed authority of the Civil Rights Com\nmission before it was created, but bitter-enders were not hap\npy about allowing its existence in any form.\nYet the fact that the job of staff director may correctly be\ntermed a hot one seems insufficient to explain the reluctance of\ncitizens to take it. A good many jobs in the federal government\nare difficult and controversial. Competent lawyer-executives,\nresponsive to the demands of the public service, are not deterred\nby apprehension of maltreatment from accepting great respon\nsibilities.\nThe question inevitably arises whether the gentlemen pre\nviously asked to take the directorship may have felt some\ndoubt about the extent of the backing that would be furnished\nby Pres. Eisenhower.\nA lack of confidence about total support from the execu\ntive department, including the President himself, would ex\nplain the curious reluctance of those approached, A man may\nbe willing to face the danger of congressional harassment if as\nsured of the all-out assistance of the Administration, He is like\nly to feel less enthusiasm for the risks if he feels he may be left\nalone while the Chief Executive stands aloof.\nThere is no specific report that doubt about presidential\nbacking is a cause of the difficulty in finding a man of stature\nwilling to take the directorship. The President clearly has a re\nsponsibility to make it clear that he wants the commission to\nfunction, vigorously and effectively, during the two years now\nallotted for its existence, and to give adequate assurance that\nhe will sustain its executives against harrassment and sniper\nfire.\n\n\nSen. Barry Goldwater, the Arizona Republican who deems\nhimself an expert on the \u201cmenace\u201d to America arising from un\nion political activity, scared Michigan Republicans recently with\na fanciful tale.\nWell-heeled gents and ladies paid $100 to GOP campaign\nfunds for the privilege of hearing him talk, and Goldwater re\ngaled them with a story of how \u201cseasoned political bosses\u201d from\nBritain's labor unions 50 years ago \u201cmoved in behind the\nfacade of the Liberal Party and took it over piece by piece\u201d un\ntil they had \u201cdigested the vitals from within.\u201d\nThis will certainly be news to Britons including Sir Win\nston Churchill, who as a Liberal Party cabinet member and\nlater as a Tory prime minister has had to face the political\nchallenge of the Labor Representation Society and later the\nLabor Party.\nBritain's unions formed an open third party, their own\nLabor Party, and for half a century have combatted both the\nLiberals and Tories. They elected the largest group of House\nof Commons members twice after World War I, squeezing out\nthe Liberal Party, and won an absolute majority during World\nWar II\nLabor is expected to win the next British election, too, but\nit will be so only if as in the past it wins the confidence of a lot\nof non-union voters. There is not, nor has there been, anything\nconspiratorial about it.\nMichigan Republicans have a legal right to hire a hall for\nGoldwater's weird interpretations of history, but it must mean\nsomething when their selected champion can't get the facta\nstraight even with all the research facilities available to him at\ntaxpayers\u2019 expense as a senator.\nit\nI\n1$\nqeAkS oo\nI\n4\nAFL-CIO\nV\neBe\nBulletin Board\nSaturday, February 8\nKIDS PARTY 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nBINGHAM 1:00 P.M. Parlor A\nIND. HEAT 7:00 P.M. Parlor B\nTOL. STAMPING 2:00 P.M. Parlor C\nPRESSED STEEL 2:00P.M. Parlor H\nSunday, February 9\nBUDDIES \u201411:00 A.M. _ Parlor A\nSKILLED TRADES 1:00 P.M. Parlor A\nPETERS STAMPING 2:00 P.M. Parlor H\nMonday, February 10\nBARRETT (night) 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nBARRETT (day) 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nBARRETT STEWARDS (night) 9:00 A.M. Parlor B\nBARRETT STEWARDS (day) 7:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSAVE ELECTRIC 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nTuesday, February 11\nPIPE THREADING OFFICE 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nSURF. COMB. 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nBARON STEEL 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nWednesday, February 12\nPENSION CLUB 12:30 P.M. Parlor A\nSUPERIOR SPINNING 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nRANSON RANOLPH 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nThursday, February 13\nSUMMER\nCAMP WOMENS GUILD 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nACME 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nCAMERA CLUB 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nDARLING 8:00 P M. Room 309\nFriday, February 14\nLOCAL NO. 12 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nBOARD OF GOVERNORS 7:00 P.M. Parlor B","height":"26828","width":"19472"}}
